<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-127-250  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 127 250.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Feb 5 1990 n286 p45(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>'800' services are booming. (Public Networking)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schultz, Beth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Astudy by the Yankee Group, Boston shows that the market for '800'services is growing at an annual rate of 12 percent.andP;  Valued at $5billion in 1987 and $7 billion in 1989, the '800' services growthhas unleashed a wave of competition as companies provide theservice to their customers in increasing numbers.andP;  Currently, ATand T holds an 83 percent market share with 930,000 numbers billedunder the FCC-mandated NXX plan.andP;  The remainder of the market isdivided between US Sprint, with about 112,000 numbers and MCICommunications Corp with 70,000.andP;  The NXX plan allows localexchange carriers to accord equal access to AT and T competitorsoffering '800' services.andP;  This arrangement will be replaced withthe implementation of Signalling System 7, which will providecentralized '800' service.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (marketing)MCI Communications Corp. (marketing)US Sprint Communications Co. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    MCIC; T.andO;Topic:     Communications Service SuppliersCommunications ApplicationsGrowthMarket ShareFCC.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Total 800-Service revenues, U.S. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>